pull_request.title: more flexible find_related() backend
pull_request.body:
This does not change existing functionality -- Section.items() behaves as it always did. Having a targetModel however gives us the ability to generically search for specific subclass model instances.

Use case assuming a typical Content->Article,Image,Video subclassed Model structure:
* Section.items will grab every Content item.
* If you only want to grab Articles, call Section.limited_items(Article)
* One problem with grabbing every Content item is you may `render_model` templatetag instances that don't have or need a requested template. On a Section page you may only want to render Articles while ignoring Image and Video.

issue.body:
Pylons seems to have bumped rev's since the last we installed.  I screwed up my virtualenv and had to reinstall.  Unfortunately when doing so, it installs the new Pylons 1.0.1rc1.  While LR seems to start up, the nosetests can't be run as the nose plugin doesn't seem to be registering for Pylons.


We either need to:

* figure out how to enable the plugin outside of the Pylons installation
* change setup.py to fixate on Pylons==1.0


My workaround was to uninstall Pylons then reinstall specifying the version number:

    pip uninstall Pylons
    pip install pylons==1.0

issue.title: Adding 'behavior.jquery' to Joomla Framework with deep non-conflict mode and support for concurrent jQuery versions running
issue.body:
Hi Joomla Framework team,

I have spent last 2 days designing and implementing a method to load jQuery frameworks, plugins and files, and non-conflicting javascript code into the document head.

The files are provided by extensions, and multiple versions are supported concurrently.

There are only 2 new public methods, one to use it and one to check that it is available (or any other JHtml::_() helper.

I have tested it with multiple jQuery frameworks and with a modified Community Builder version too.

I feel that the changes to existing code and functionality (including minor bug fixes and php-lint fixes) are safe enough for Joomla 2.5.

Please review and comment, main description is below:

Best Regards,
Beat


	/**
	 * Method to load jQuery frameworks and non-conflicting javascript code into the document head
	 * Loading and use is done in "deep non-conflict mode", which allows several concurent versions of jQuery to be loaded and run simultaneously with any other javascript framework, including another conflicting jQuery instance.
	 * It means that the window's Javascript global namespace is not used in a fixed way: neither $ nor jQuery global variables are used. Reference: http://api.jquery.com/jQuery.noConflict/
	 * 
	 * Calling and params:
	 * JHTml::_('behavior.jquery', $fullVersion, $relativePathToRoot, $listofPlugins, $javascriptCodeToRunInNonConflictMode);
	 * 
	 * Use: Example:
	 * JHTml::_('behavior.jquery', '1.6.1', 'media/jquery/', null, '$("p").css("color","red")');
	 * JHTml::_('behavior.jquery', '1.7.0', 'media/othercompon/js/', array('jquery.flot','jquery.form'));;
	 * JHTml::_('behavior.jquery', '1.7.1', 'media/mycomponent/jquery/', array('jquery.ui-all','jquery.form'),'$("h1,h2,h3").css("color","green")');
	 * Will load jQuery 1.6.1 with ui and form from the 1.7.1 folder media/mycomponent/jquery, and and jQuery 1.7.1 with flot and form from the 1.7.0 folder media/othercompon/jquery
	 *
	 * If debugging mode is on an uncompressed version of jQuery is included for easier debugging.
	 * Files: 2 files are mandatory for jquery and jQuery plugins, and do follow the jQuery naming:
	 * jQuery: jquery-1.7.1.js for uncompressed and jquery-1.7.1.min.js
	 * jQuery plugins: "$path/$pluginname[.min].js"
	 *
	 * @param   string         $version        x.y.z jQuery-Version (not jQuery plugins versions, but always jQuery one) corresponding to the file to load (highest sub-version Z of same x.y release will be loaded in the end) [MANDATORY]
	 * @param   string         $path           Path to file from root of website (no / at start but / at end) so that it can be appended to absolute files path or live site [MANDATORY ONCE AT LEAST]
	 * @param   array|null     $jQueryPlugins  Array of filenames (without .js or .min.js extension) of jQuery plugins or other Javascript files with jQuery code (which need the jQuery and $ to be defined correctly) [optional]
	 * @param   string|null    $jqCode         jQuery Javascript code outputed in context with jQuery and $ defined and on dom ready [optional]
	 *
	 * @return  void
	 *
	 * @since   11.5
	 */


	/**
	 * Checks if a JHtml::_($key) call can be made.
	 * If the function is not registered, tries to load the corresponding class without registering the function.
	 * 
	 * @param   string  $key  The name of helper method to load, (prefix).(class).function
	 *                        prefix and class are optional and can be used to load custom
	 *                        html helpers.
	 *
	 * @return  boolean      True: $key function is implemented, False: is not.
	 */
	JHtml::isCallable_($key)

comment.body:
Hi Rouven,

To reply on your feedbacks:

1. Yes, it *does also* solve the problem of running smoothly side-by-side mootools *and* jQuery. The goal is *not* to replace Mootools, nor to use jQuery for Joomla core behaviors here.

2. This proposal is exactly meant for Joomla to not need to do any jQuery version tracking, as that code does it between the extensions' proposals automatically. That's why there is a bit of code (not that much actually).

3. Prescript and Postscript are needed to put jQuery in non-conflict mode (that's why most extensions do conflict).

4.  JHtml::isCallable_() allows to check if any JHtml::_($key) can be called without errors, typically, before calling the 'behavior.jquery' with JHtml::_('behavior.jquery, ....) from an extension, you can test it like this, e.g.:

```php
if ( JHtml::isCallable_('behavior.jquery' ) ) {
	JHtml::_('behavior.jquery', _MY_JQUERY_VERSION, '_MY_PATH_TO_MY_JQUERY_VERSION, $jQueryPlugins)
}
else
{
	old way...
}
```

So it's not used in the Framework itself, but useful to know if a behavior is supported.

A jQuery plugin that replaces Mootools for core behaviors can make sense, but won't solve the same problem that is the most urgent ones:

1. Running smoothly Mootools and jQuery side-by-side

2. Running smoothly multiple incompatible jQuery versions concurrently: Extension A requires jQuery 1.5.x, while module B requires jQuery 1.7.x

3. Avoiding 4 times same jQuery version loaded: e.g. no need to load 1.7.0 2 times and 1.7.1 3 times on a page, loading once latest maintenance release 1.7.1 of jQuery will make all extensions happy.

4. Making it easy to load and use your jQuery version without any conflicts. Loading jQuery in a non-conflict mode is hard (Joomla framework does not allow Pre/Post-scripts, and it's not well documented), and loading deep-non-conflict is very hard. That leads to bad imlementations leading to conflicts with Joomla's Mootools and between extensions too.

5. Having an official standard way to solve the above.

Only way to achieve that is in Joomla core, and it does require a few lines of code. Hope that my comments on the code are clear. Let me know if something is unclear :)

issue.body:
After upgrading to the newest version of Infinitest recently, I noticed that if any of my tests fail (for any reason), the error in the Problems tab is "NoClassDefFoundError (com/google/common/base/String)". Note that in no way do any of my projects' code nor dependencies have a dependency (direct or otherwise) on Guava. But I can make the problem go away by adding Guava to my project's classpath. Also note that the correct test failure message is given when doing the build outside of the IDE with Maven or Gradle.

I've seen this happen on several projects since upgrading to the newest Infinitest, but here's are some details of one place where I know it to happen:

 - I'm using SpringSource ToolSuite v2.8.1.RELEASE, with Infinitest 5.1.98 installed.
 - I create a new Spring Utility Project (File->New->Spring Template Project and then choose "Simple Spring Utility Project").
 - Initially all of the tests given in the template project pass, so there is no problem.
 - I change any of the tests, forcing it to fail ("Assert.assertTrue(false);", for example)
 - I see the aforementioned NoClassDefFoundError in the Problems tab.

Given the timing of when these errors started appearing (after upgrading Infinitest), I believe this to be a bug in Infinitest. I should not have to add Guava to my project's classpath in order for failed test messages to properly display.

issue.title: buf.rewind() in WebSocket.channelWrite breaks partially written buffers
issue.body:
I'm using Java-WebSocket to write a [websockify](https://github.com/kanaka/websockify) implementation in Java.  I'm using it to run VNC data to [noVNC](http://kanaka.github.com/noVNC/).  It was pretty quick and easy to implement, but my data would get corrupted after a little while and the VNC client would shut down with data errors.

I tracked this down to a problem with partially written buffers.  WebSocket.sendFrame will attempt to write a buffer with channelWrite.  If the buffer is only partially written it will be placed on a queue and the next time sendFrame is called the rest of the buffer will be sent.  The problem is that channelWrite rewinds the buffer, so it resends the portion of the buffer that was already sent.

In my opinion, channelWrite should not change the state of the buffer.  Buffers should be prepared for writing out to the socket before getting to channelWrite.  Partially written buffers will then be continued from the correct location.

issue.title: cannot look at attributes for nonexistent files
issue.body:
The attribute code calls git_path_prettify on the path component provided by the caller. In turn, this calls realpath() on the path, which will fail if the file does not actually exist. Upstream git will happily report the attributes whether or not the file exists.

I ran across this because the upstream git test suite constructs gitattributes files without making the related files in the filesystem.  But I believe it would also be a problem for any bare repository (which won't have .gitattributes files, but should still respect $GIT_DIR/info/attributes).

/cc @arrbee

comment.body: Okay, so 6a67a812c224878483659c6f25ca21573d1c309b should fix the issue, allowing checks of both attributes and ignores for files regardless of whether they actually exist. I'll close this issue when the gitignore branch is merged. Thanks again for pointing this out!

issue.title: consider making UTF8 / LF default for .pp files
issue.body:
Since the most common platform for puppet is Linux, and people perform editing on Windows, they are bitten by the fact that they do not get files that are UTF8 and with LF endings by default.

Most users probably want this.

Not sure how easy it is to set this by default (as opposed to like it is now with default being the platform defaults where Geppetto runs). Maybe it is possible to override this in packaged Geppetto. When installing in the IDE, it is really the IDE that decides.

We should make notes in the FAQ as well how people should work with line endings and encoding.
